                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Regarding your conundrum:</p>

<p>Minute Rice is a brand of parboiled rice. It takes less time to cook because it has already been boiled in the husk. I have never cooked whole grain organic rice, but I believe it hasn't be parboiled. Because Minute Rice has already been boiled in the husk, it takes less time for the rice to become saturated; I imagine that this is not the case with whole grain organic rice. Once the rice is saturated and the residual water has boiled away, the temperature of the rice exceeds the boiling point, thus tripping the thermostat in the rice cooker--the rice cooker then switches to "Warming". Since it takes less time for the Minute Rice to become saturated, it achieves the "Warming" state faster than the whole grain organic rice. Of course, that's just one theory. Personally, I'm a fan of the Intelligent Pot.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
