                            <span class="vcard author">Vijay</span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-540367"><abbr class="published" title="2008-11-02T01:27:47-06:00">November  2, 2008  1:27 AM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(540367, 'Vijay')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Pot Overflow:  Anybody who uses pot regulary would have atleast experienced the overflowing pot once. <br />
This phenomenon is mostly seen with new users or users who try to use a 3 cup pot to prepare a thanksgiving dinner for kith and kin. The first time it happens it is quite tense experience.  It is an ugly and messy sight.</p>

<p> Do you the exact amount of rice and water to add to your pot, such that  the rice, when it is fully, cooked just pushes the lid up without the rice or water spilling over. Until you know this, you don't know your pot !!!!! And you better know your pot.</p>

<p>Vijay</p>
