                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>My rice cooker was indispensable the years I lived in Japan. </p>

<p>In Japan I cooked rice in it, of course. In the morning I used it to make hot rice to eat with nato. In the evening for the meal's rice. I also made miso soup in it. I cooked cracked wheat in it when I wanted an American-style breakfast. I warmed up cabbage and onions in it, steamed hakusai cabbage or Chinese broccoli. I made a Chinese dish called mama-dofu -- kind of a spicy sauce with lots of tofu in it.</p>

<p>We got one for a wedding present here in the States. It was the best gift and lasted much longer than the cash we got at the reception.</p>

<p>My daughter is moving to Germany in December. She'll live in a small apartment with no counter space. Now I know what I'm getting her for Christmas. </p>
                </div>
