                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p><br />
Richard Kaufman - </p>

<p>According to the BBC's <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/branding/pdf/writing_style_guidelines_jan06.pdf">Writing Style Guidelines</a>, "(P)unctuation at the end of a sentence comes inside the quotation marks if the quote is a full sentence."  Otherwise, the BBC tends to place punctuation, including full stops, outside of the quotation marks.  If the punctuation is part of the quote, it remains inside the quotation marks.  The full stop, by the way, cannot end a quoted sentence when it does not also end the actual sentence, in which case, the replacement comma is inside the quotation marks as per the above rule.</p>

<p><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/us_elections_2008/7707581.stm">Case in point.</a></p>

<p>Personally, I use <i>typesetters' quotation</i> because the alternative, <i>logical quotation</i>, just doesn't feel right.<br />
  </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
