                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Roger, I don't have a proper kitchen, so I use my pot to cook pasta, rice and lentils. The only bad thing about the pot is that it is limited to boiling. This means that you can't create the fried base of onions and garlic that classic soups usually have. Apart from that, the pot is perfect. I couldn't live without it.</p>

<p><b> Ebert: I have done this. Spray the Teflon pot with low fat Pam (olive oil type). Add a little olive oil and chopped onion and garlic. Close and heat. Don't allow onions to burn. You can open briefly to stir onions a little, and check on progress. Monitor  closely, and have other soup ingredients all ready to add. </b></p>
                </div>
            </div>
