                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I've been using a rice cooker since forever, but I bought my first neuro-fuzzy Zojirushi a year ago. </p>

<p>It really is worth the extra money and learning curve.</p>

<p>I use the timer feature frequently.  (Mine has two memories, which I set for breakfast or dinner time.)   That way, I can wake up to fresh oatmeal or grits, or come home from work with dinner ready.  </p>

<p>You set the time you want your food to be ready, put in your dried goods and water, and let it do its magic.</p>

<p>I presoak dried beans the night before, set the timer for when I get home from work the next night and the brown rice setting and, presto!<br />
(It's also the most energy-efficient way to cook dried beans.)</p>

<p>Steel-cut oatmeal and grits cook on the porridge setting.</p>

<p>Magic.  </p>

<p>BTW, I work in a CS research group.  All the guys have the neuro-fuzzy and love it, but we have no idea what kind of algorithm Zojirushi uses.  Perhaps it is a trade secret.</p>

<p>Last time I visited my mom, she had a bought herself a neuro-fuzzy Zojirushi, too.  She said that it was the best rice cooker she's ever owned.  Too bad she had to wait 70 years to learn that.<br />
</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
