                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Roger,</p>

<p>My sainted mother taught me to rinse all white rice twice. Swish it for twenty seconds or so, drain, then rinse again. Then cover the rice with enough water to the level of one knuckle. For some reason this rule of, er, knuckle, works whether you're using a plain pot on a stove or a rice cooker and whether you're making three cups or eight. It always worked for us. I've got two generations of restaurateurs on both sides of my family and that's how they did it. (My maternal grandfather was the maitre'd of the original Ruby Foo's on Broadway.)</p>

<p>I am the only one in my family who will eat brown rice. Even my cardiologist and my internist -- both Asian-Americans -- prefer white rice, but they applaud my choice.</p>

<p>The next time you make your rice, add a handful of lentils. They add a nice little flavor note and a bit more fiber. Sometimes, to change things up, I'll drain the liquid off a can of chopped tomatoes (saving the tomatoes for another recipe) and add a pinch of cumin. I also like to cut off the stumps of my cauliflower or broccoli and chop them up into chunks and add them to rice as it cooks. I would rather eat the florets on their own.</p>

<p>Thank you, kenn</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
