                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>To make terrific french onion soup:</p>

<p>Buy six pounds of short ribs.  Rub with salt, pepper, and any herbs you like (marjoram is good).  Roast in a pyrex pan for about 7 hours at 220 degrees.  Yes, I said 220 degrees.  </p>

<p>They will come out beautifully browned, roasted, and the meat will be coming off the bones.</p>

<p>Put meat and bones into The Pot with 1/2 bunch of celery, cut up.  Cover with fresh, lightly salted water to make about 8 cups.  Cook overnight on low, low simmer.  In the morning strain out bones, meat, et al, and add about 6 medium carrots, peeled and sliced.  Cook for the remainder of the day.</p>

<p>Decant the mixture, strain out cooked carrots, and put broth in the refrigerator.  In the morning, you can easily lift off the caked tallow from the surface, and you're left with a rich, brown, virtually fatless broth.</p>

<p>If you do everything properly, you will end up with about six cups or so.</p>

<p>Use the broth as a base for Julia Child's French Onion Soup recipe (http://www.grouprecipes.com/24870/julia-child-french-onion-soup.html), and you will have a soup for the ages...</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
