                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Great piece, Roger. I'd like to add a bit to the origin story for Worcestershire Sauce. The colonel did indeed serve in India, fell in love with the original version and prevailed upon the local producers to give him the recipe. Dreaming of building a lucrative business, once back in England, he hired Mr. Lea and Mr. Perrins to assemble the ingredients. When the task was complete, the chemists contacted the colonel, who sampled the batch and pronounced that it "tastes like dirt!" Thinking that the apothecaries had failed in their task, he angrily left without paying them, leaving them with several barrels of the stuff. Several weeks passed before they got to the task of disposing of the mixture. In that time the fermentation process occurred, transforming the dirt tasting mixture into the savory elixer we all now enjoy with our grilled cheese. I don't what happened to the colonel.<br />
</p>
                </div>
