                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I know I'm way too late with the recipes. But I too am a huge rice-cooker fan. </p>

<p>Unlike many cooks, I have never had trouble making perfect rice on the stove-top. I got a rice cooker because it had a timer feature and I wanted to have fresh rice ready to go with the curry in the slowcooker after a long workday, and there for my family even if I got home late. Now I use it all the time as it's so easy. I usually measure the water, but I think the one-knuckle rule works fine too (and it's doable in the rice cooker because the water is cold, not boiling, when the measuring is done). </p>

<p>The other thing I use it for (aside from the overnight steel-cut oats) is cooking polenta, which is comfort food from my Balkan heritage. I realized this was possible when I read how the cookers actually work (boils till the water is gone, then drops to low). I bring the water to a boil, then open the lid and add a cup or two of cornmeal, which I have already saturated with cold water. Stir in, cover, and test when it switches to low; if it still has an uncooked taste I add a few spoons of water which tricks the heating element to turn back on. This is the easiest way to do polenta--there is no whisking, no standing and stirring, no lumps--so revolutionizes it much more than it does the cooking of rice.</p>

<p>The other thing that works in it is South African-style white cornmeal porridge or "mielie-meal", which is eaten as the grain staple with meat and sauce. The cooking technique is different--measure cold water and add the meal to it, cook till it switches to warm setting and keep it there for at least 30 minutes so it gets a bit crusty at the edges. I've never had grits, and I'm curious which cornmeal-cooking method is closer to the way to cook grits.</p>

<p><b> Ebert: I like your empirical approach: When first trying it, stand by to add some water. Also, use chicken broth, etc., if you want flavor.</b> </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
        <div id="comment-978160" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author">Nick</span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-978160"><abbr class="published" title="2010-07-17T17:35:42-06:00">July 17, 2010  5:35 PM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(978160, 'Nick')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I thank you for this ebert, as an unemployed, creative, drifter (loser) who has no future plans for settling down any time soon. I've owned this thing for three days and already I've made oatmeal, chili, breakfast skillets, stir frys and chili. I'm an absolute convert of minimalist cooking, in fact before this I cooked all of my meals in a single small pan over the stove.</p>

<p>I submit this one very simple, healthy, cheap recipe:</p>

<p>Pseudo-italian chicken and mushroom chili (emphasis on it being pseudo italian, not pseudo chicken chili)</p>

<p>1 can chili beans in sauce (I buy the Bush's brand, it's cheap)<br />
1 can italian diced tomatoes, with water<br />
1 lb chicken breast (I buy it in bulk frozen<br />
1/2 cup mushrooms, chopped (best if precooked or canned)<br />
Chili powder<br />
Flour (Or any thickening agent)<br />
Jalapenos* (Omit if you don't like spicy food)<br />
Pepper to taste</p>

<p>Cook up the chicken, jalapenos* and the mushrooms in some water at the bottom of the pot. Once it has boiled up remove the chicken and chop it to bits. Then throw in your can of tomatoes and chili, let that boil up and add in some more water if it looks too thin. After a few minutes of boiling up add in your chili powder to taste and 1-3 tbsp of flour (Depending on how much sauce you want) And stir it up and let it sit there for however long you want everything to meld together. </p>

<p>This makes me four servings for less than four dollars (Well in Florida i have no idea how much this stuff costs elsewhere) it tastes like a mixture between traditional chili and minestrone. I eat it every day. Good deal. </p>

<p><b> Ebert: You've got the spirit.</b></p>

<p><b>P.S. No one who is creative is a loser.</b> </p>
                </div>
            </div>
