                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Just read the article in the NY Times, pre-ordered the book, and started in on this blog.  Well, I have a larger rice cooker and it cooks rice wonderfully, but I never tried it even once for anything else.  It never occurred to me.  I thought I'd give it all a try.  Here's what I did:  I had about a pound of beef stew meat frozen in the fridge.  I dumped it in the cooker frozen, found some beef broth (did the smell test -- it passed) and poured it in.  Found some celery and parsley which I chopped roughly and threw it in.  Added a variety of spices from my cabinet like Greek seasoning, dash of Cajun, onion salt, some garlic from a jar, several dashes of Worchestershire sauce and topped it all off with some basmati rice, which I totally forgot to wash.  About two hours later and my, my, MY what a wonderful and quick meal I turned out.  My lady -- a Senegalese used to rice dishes -- came by and marvelled at my concoction.  Success, success, success!  And I didn't even break a sweat!  Thank you King Roger.  My next child will be named after you.</p>
