                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>A few days ago I reported a successful use of my rice cooker (see above posting).  I'm a total kitchen klutz and was delighted that the rice cooker seemed to be klutz-proof.  Well, I tried Mr. Ebert's oatmeal basics today and, man, did I have a not-so-wonderful experience.  I went to my local big-to-do health food market looking for "stone ground" oatmeal.  Well, they had every variation under the sun EXCEPT stone ground.  So I opted for "steel cut," whatever the heck that is.  For one serving they suggested 1/4 cup of oatmeal, pretty puny for a manly man such as myself, so I doubled it to 1/2 cup and the 3 cups water the box directions called for.  Turned the rice cooker on and went back to my Sunday paper (the news wasn't particularly good today, I might add).  I heard the "click" and went to check out the pot.  It had boiled over big time, a slurmy mess all over my kitchen counter, dripping down onto the cabinet underneath.  Not fun cleaning all that up.  So I decided to give the resulting oatmeal the taste test.  Mr. Ebert likes his oatmeal "al dente."  What I ate was hard enough to break your dentes.  It felt like I was eating cattle feed.  I've never had a boil over before with my rice cooker.  So oatmealers, beware that you may be limited to a very small serving unless you want a mess on your hands.  And you may want to stick with the "Better For Thee Than Me" guy rather than the expensive box of cow chow I bought from the health food emporium.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
        <div id="comment-1050238" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://www.duncanhbrown.com" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=1050238">Duncan Brown</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-1050238"><abbr class="published" title="2010-09-15T15:43:48-06:00">September 15, 2010  3:43 PM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(1050238, 'Duncan Brown')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Duncans Barley Dal Recipe<br />
(You can also make Kicheree by substituting Rice for the Barley)</p>

<p>1. Rice Cooker <br />
Start with a Rice Cooker with a Steamer Insert (I use a Lotus Foods-brand Rice Cooker, $80, solid stainless steel, purchased from the At Home Store in Fairfield, Iowa). Theres also a Stainless Steel Rice Cooker available at the MUM Bookstore, and at Everybodys, for $70. The Miracle Exclusives Rice Cooker is available from Amazon.com for $60 plus shipping. All of these are very similar; stainless steel throughout, same warm/cook switch, same steamer tray.</p>

<p>2.a Recipe (based on 1 cup dry ingredientsmodify all amounts based on amount of dry ingredients)</p>

<p>2.b. Quantity<br />
Makes 48 oz (approx. 4-6 servings) </p>

<p>2.c. Ingredients and Preparation<br />
	1/2 cup pearled barley (organic preferred, from Whole Foods, $2/lb. You can use hulled barley, but it doesnt plump up as nice because it has the hull still on it.)<br />
	1/2 cup split mung dal (organic preferred, I get mine from Everybody's in Fairfield, Iowa in 25-lb bags for ca. $65 plus shipping. It lasts forever.) [Dal is a high-protein Legume like Peas or Lentils. It is very popular in India; there are many types of Dal available; I like Mung Dal.]<br />
	Put the barley and dal in the cooking pan. Add water and swirl around the water to wash the dry ingredients. Then pour the water out. Repeat 2-3 more times or until the water is clear, not cloudy. Pour off the clear water.)<br />
	Add 4 cups of pure good-tasting water to the rice cooker pan. (If you can plan ahead, set aside the water and grains to soak overnight; this step is not critical, but nice. It makes the cooking time shorter and is said to reduce the gas in the dal.)<br />
	Add 2 tbsp oil (prefer extra virgin olive oil, or grape seed oil, or sesame oil, or ghee (clarified butter). This oil is the secret ingredient that helps stop your rice cooker from making a mess on the counter and the floor when the dal/rice/barley boils and threatens to overflow.<br />
	2-3 tsp of Maharishi Ayurveda Vata, Pita or Kapha Churna (seasoning). This is a spice/herb mixture with calming (vata) cooling (pita) or stimulating (kapha) qualities. I use Vata or Pitta Churna. (Available from the Health and Wholeness Store in Fairfield, Iowa, ca. $15 for the 8-oz. (large) size plus shipping. (You can also buy generic Pitah, Vatah, and Kaphah spice mixtures at Everybody's, Fairfield, IA.) (Note: Vata Churna Ingredients: Cumin, Ginger, Fenugreek, Turmeric, Turbinado Sugar, Salt, and Asafoetida (Hing) in a Rice-flower base; Pitta Churna Ingredients: Coriander, Fennel, Cumin, Turbinado Sugar, Cardamom, Ginger, Turmeric, Cinnamon, and Salt. Kapha Churna Ingredients: Ginger, Pepper, Coriander, Turbinado Sugar, Turmeric, Salt and Cinnamon.) <br />
	1 tsp ground ginger powder<br />
	1 tsp ground fennel<br />
	1-3 tsp whole fennel seeds (adds nice texture)<br />
	a couple of healthy shakes of ground turmeric<br />
	a couple of shakes of ground coriander [optional; this is also in Vata or Pitta Churna]<br />
	a couple of shakes of ground cumin [optional; this is also in Vata or Pitta Churna]<br />
	 tsp of Asafoetida (aka Hing), ground fine (I get mine from Everybody's in Fairfield, IA. This is a pungent ingredient made from a crystallized plant sap that adds a lot of flavor with just a little bit added.)<br />
	Several whole Bay Leaves (discard after cooking)<br />
	Several Curry Leaves (adds a pungent flavor)<br />
	1/8-1/4 tsp of Sea Salt or Real Salt, or none and salt/pepper to taste at table). [optional; I avoid all salt in cooking]<br />
	1 tbsp of chopped dried Chives<br />
	1 tbsp chopped dried Cilantro<br />
	1 tbsp chopped dried basil</p>

<p>3. Cooking<br />
	Plug in the Ricer Cooker. Turn on the switch for cooking on the rice cooker (with the Lotus, flip the switch down).<br />
	Add the steamer insert on top of the cooking pan. Wash and dice up your favorite vegetables.<br />
	Some of My Favorite Vegetables:<br />
o	A couple of carrots (always)<br />
o	Some stalks of celery (very good, diced small) (often)<br />
o	 a head of cauliflower diced small (sometimes)<br />
o	A stalk of broccoli diced small (sometimes). <br />
o	1/4-1/2 pound of asparagus diced small (delish) (sometimes)<br />
o	A couple of small potatoes diced small (instead of the cauliflower/broccoli) (sometimes) (starchy, but tasty; I have them 1-2 times/wklots of potassium)<br />
o	5-15 Brussels sprouts (diced smaller if large) (a nice variation instead of broccoli) (sometimes)<br />
o	Greens like chard or bokchoi (excellent, finely chopped). (sometimes)<br />
o	A handful of green beans diced small (sometimes)<br />
o	etc. etc. Pick your favorites, try them out.<br />
	Go and meditate (or whatever).<br />
	45 minutes to 1 hr. later, it's all ready. After it finishes the main cooking cycle, it automatically switches to warm. So, no burning the cooking pan (or your food). You can leave it to cook further for up to an hour after the 45-minute cooking phase finishes with no bad results. Unplug the Rice Cooker. Stir the Barley Dal, then stir in the veggies. You're now ready to eat, or to scoop it into a wide-mouth food Thermos (I own two 24-oz. Thermos-Brand Stainless steel wide-mouth food thermoses (I got the latest one from Amazon.com). The Barley Dal with Veggies recipe described above fills them both up neatly.<br />
	Note on grains: You can vary the grains. For instance, you can substitute Organic Brown Basmati Rice for the Barley. Since the dal takes 45 minutes to cook, I use a matched grain that also takes a similar time to cook. (This is why I dont use Quinoa or White Basmati rice.) Wild rice is wonderful as well; it also takes about 45 minutes to cook. (Ive tried 1/3 cup dal, 1/3 cup brown rice, and 1/3 cup wild riceit came out great! Ive also tried 1/3 cup dal, 1/3 cup brown rice, and 1/3 cup barleyagain, delicious!).  cup wild rice,  cup dal,  cup pearled barley, and  cup brown rice was quite good, also.<br />
	Note on dal: You can use split peas or split lentils or other types of dal instead of mung dal. I just really like the taste of mung dal.<br />
	Note on Dal boiling over: Dal has a tendency when cooked by itself in a rice cooker (or in a pan on the stove for that matter) to boil over and make a mess on your stove or countertop. Ways to prevent this: 1) Cock the lid of the rice cooker or pot so that the dal doesnt boil over. 2) Put 1-3 TBSP of oil into the Dal at the start of cooking 3) Put vegetables (or whatever) in the steamer insert above the cooking pan. This will prevent the overflow altogether. 5) Put the Rice Cooker onto a plate so that, if there is any overflow, it ends up on the plate and not on your counter 6) Dont cook the Dal all by itself. The addition of Barley and or Rice and or Wild Rice seems to prevent or reduce boil-over.<br />
	The grain provides the texture; the legume provides the soup-like quality.</p>

<p>Duncan H. Brown<br />
Web: www.duncanhbrown.com<br />
E-mail: duncan@duncanhbrown.com<br />
</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
