                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Ok, I got my rice cooker a few weeks ago, the Zojirushi 10 cup, and the rice I've made has turned out great, including brown rice and a rice mixture from Costco.  When I went to make oatmeal this morning I wanted to try making it in The Pot but wasn't sure about a couple things so I chickened out.  First, if a person is making something other than rice, like oatmeal, should I still always measure using the "cup" that came with the rice cooker as a cup of oatmeal or whatever?  Obviously the cup that came with it isn't actually a cup in measurements.  I'm not like Aunt Mary and am a little nervous about experiments but I'm going to try to be more willing to try as I get to know my Pot.  I did put cut up bananas and peaches on my husbands oatmeal though instead of brown sugar and he seemed to like it.  Baby steps!  By the way, I got your book last Wednesday and love it!<br />
Cheryl</p>

<p><b> Ebert: Doesn't matter. It's one Thingie of oatmeal to two Thingies of water. Or maybe two and a splash. Be sure to add some fruit or berries. A banana and some blueberries, for example.</b> </p>
