                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Yesterday, my husband and I traveled to St. Pete. Florida to celebrate my mothers 91st birthday.  Minutes after we arrived, she showed off a book she had been on the waiting list to receive...'The Pot...'</p>

<p>We were taking her to an old Greek fishing village for lunch, (an hours drive), and I while she and my husband chatted, I sat in the back seat and read the entire book.</p>

<p>Had a wonderful lunch in Tarpon Springs, Fl., and on the way back, she asked that we stop and get 'the pot.'  I ran into a mega-store and bought the simplest one they had...Then another stop to buy rice, oatmeal and lentils.</p>

<p>Upon arriving back at her house, we proceeded to make oatmeal, and the words 'the pot knows' became the slogan of the day.</p>

<p>Have to share this though...Years ago I took many cooking classes from a Chinese woman and she showed how to make perfect rice every time using any one pot and no measuring instruments. </p>

<p> Also, the reason for rinsing the rice is to remove starch.  If you want the rice to be separate, fluffy,  and not sticky then rinse off the starch.  If you want the rice to be sticky and sweet, don't rinse.  </p>

<p>Thank for the book Roger...She's going to have fun with it,<br />
Katie</p>

<p><b> Ebert: The Pot is Happy.</b> </p>
