                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>My gigantic crock pot can swallow your puny rice cooker in one bite! BWAA! HA! HA!</p>

<p>Anyway, contributions to the war against low-salt blandness follow:</p>

<p>01. The best, as usual, comes from Trader's Joes. Try the "21 Seasoning Salute". Absolutely amazing - no salt. Trader Joe's also makes a Chile Pepper Sauce with zero sodium. Zero. </p>

<p>02. The Spice Hunter brand has about a dozen no-salt seasoning mixes, some of which are pretty good. </p>

<p>03. McIlhenny's original pepper sauce has only 1% USRDA sodium (compared with the 3% in Lee & Perrins worcestershire). </p>

<p>People may say that they don't like hot sauce, but they should get the Chile Pepper Sauce from Trader Joes and the McIlhenny's original pepper sauce anyway. If you add *tiny* amounts of chile/pepper sauce to anything, you get the sensation that your food contains salt (even though it doesn't) but without the heat. The no-salt chile sauce from Trader Joe's is so good that I'd like to have it tested in a lab 'cuz I'm suspicious of anything that perfect. </p>

<p>Kudos on your Pulitzer, Hemingway.</p>

<p><b> Ebert: Few people know that Lea & Perrins Worcestershire is  very low salt, and its "no salt" version even lower. You really don't need salt.</b> </p>
