                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>One thing I'm a tad surprised that no one's mentioned yet is use of a pot as tool for steamboat (or if you must 'chinese fondue' or 'hot pot'. Not what we called it back home mind you) - and for this, the simpler the better, fuzzly logic be dammed.</p>

<p>Such things really do lend themselves to cold winter evenings with friends and family sitting round a table talking about whatever you do. The pot takes pride of place in the centre, filled with water gently boiling and bubbling away while each throws in whatever is handy - vegetables, noodles, meats, eggs - and picks it out when done to their liking. </p>

<p>By it's very nature, you tend to jostle arms a bit, and you have to accept that someone is going to pluck out that perfectly cooked egg you've been giving just a moment longer to cook <i>(sigh)</i> but that's half the fun and by night's end, you've inevitably eaten your fill and there's a lovely soup in the pot from all those bits in and out of the pot.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
