        <div id="comment-1494343" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://notexactlyaquote.tumblr.com" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=1494343">Sam</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-1494343"><abbr class="published" title="2011-01-08T19:12:36-06:00">January  8, 2011  7:12 PM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(1494343, 'Sam')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I read How to Use the Pot last night. It was fantastic. I wrote about it in my blog if you or any of your readers are interested in reading it.<br />
http://notexactlyaquote.tumblr.com/post/2650488369/the-pot-and-how-to-use-it-a-book-review-and-more</p>

<p>Tonight, Im going to depart from my norm of posting movie reviews, and try my hand with a book review. The book in question: The Pot and How to Use it: The Mystery and Romance of the Rice Cooker by Roger Ebert.</p>

<p>Several of my posts have referenced my admiration of Mr. Ebert. As Ive said, he is one of two sources of inspiration on my beloved topic of film. But that is not the subject of his book or of my post. It is that of the rice cooker.</p>

<p>Eberts recent battle with cancer resulted in a surgery removing his lower jaw and depriving him of the ability to speak or eat. This in turn resulted in him taking on a more massive online presence. He is Twitter and Facebook and he created a new blog where he discusses a myriad of topics, not strictly film. I am a regular reader. One of his recent posts was about his upcoming book on the rice cooker.</p>

<p>I told Mom about the post under the misconception it was referring to a crock pot. She bought me one for Christmas and I later bought Eberts book to accompany the gift. Upon glancing through the book, we realized that it was talking about the rice cooker not the crockpot. In my ignorance I had thought they were the same thing. Apparently theyre not. Dont worry, Im sure my crock pot will come in handy and be well-used too. So we went off to Wal-Mart to locate the proper appliance:a Rival six-cup rice cooker for thirteen bucks (Mom even got herself one  an Aroma eight cup rice cooker for a few dollars more). We went home and experimented with them cooking eggs in mine and long grain brown rice in Moms. By the way, Ive since learned the difference between a crock pot and a rice cooker. The crock pot is a slow cooker with a thermostat.The ingredients are be placed in the pot at the beginning of the day, turned on, and it will all be ready by dinnertime. The rice cooker, on the other hand, has just two settings: cook and warm. So it cooks the meal then keeps it warm til youre ready to serve. Consider yourself informed.</p>

<p>This is ostensibly a book review, so lets finally talk about the book, more about me later. Roger Ebert is a Pulitzer Prize winning author; he was the first film critic to win the Pulitzer and remained the only one for twenty-eight years. So, theoretically, I dont have to tell you that he is a great writer. You wouldnt expect a film critic to write a book about cooking, but he did and he brings the same natural and witty style of writing he uses in his film reviews. But even his cookbook is rife with film references, which made it all the more enjoyable for me, the film buff that I am.  Ebert writes of how the rice cooker can be used by people short on time, money and space to cook healthy and tasty meals. But he is quick to say that hes not putting his readers on an all rice diet. In fact, he claims that practically anything can be cooked in the rice cooker. The book is a really quick read; I got through it in less than three hours tonight. Mom, for you and any other health nutsuhhealth conscious people, the book is a proponent of locally grown, organic food and names books and websites with information on finding community gardens, edible school yards, and farmers markets in your area. I noticed while writing this review, Ebert always refers to the Pot with the capital P as if it was a deity of some sort. That gives you an idea of the esteem he holds for this appliance.</p>

<p>When I first moved to Carlsbad, over a year and a half ago, I lived on microwaveable dinners. A few months ago, I finally got myself a Foreman Grill which has improved my daily cuisine some. And I anticipate the Pot improving this bachelors life as well. Thanks Roger</p>

<p><b> Ebert: Now the Foreman Grill! Man!</b> </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
