                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://www.simplicityandfrugality.blogspot.com" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=1508843">Jill</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-1508843"><abbr class="published" title="2011-01-10T18:05:52-06:00">January 10, 2011  6:05 PM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(1508843, 'Jill')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I'm a latecomer to this post...but my friend just confessed to making "bathtub caulk" by making "Minute Rice" in her rice cooker.  I wondered why anyone would bother making instant rice in a rice cooker and a web-search of this led me here.<br />
I've sent her the link to try to help her along with her cooking adventures.  <br />
I got my rice cooker at a thrift store.  It was practically brand new and cost 5$.  I'm still using it a few times a week after 4 years.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
        <div id="comment-1745328" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://www.japanesericecookers.net" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=1745328">Andrew</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-1745328"><abbr class="published" title="2011-02-09T08:44:46-06:00">February  9, 2011  8:44 AM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(1745328, 'Andrew')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>I am still fiddling with my oatmeat:water ratio as well as choosing different settings to cook it with. There is a fine line between dry oatmeal and gooey oatmeal bubbling out the top of my rice cooker!</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
        <div id="comment-2126044" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://carefuleugene.blogspot.com" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=2126044">Paul Arrand Rodgers</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-2126044"><abbr class="published" title="2011-03-26T13:03:55-06:00">March 26, 2011  1:03 PM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(2126044, 'Paul Arrand Rodgers')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>This is a somewhat dead thread, but here goes nothing.</p>

<p>Just made this for lunch:</p>

<p>2 cups of elbow macaroni<br />
1 cup of heavy cream<br />
1 cup of chicken broth<br />
1/2 cup of shredded cheese<br />
2 tablespoons of butter<br />
Salt, pepper, crushed red pepper, hot sauce to taste.</p>

<p>I threw everything into the pot (even the cheese), and it came out perfectly. All told, the ingredients to make 6-8 servings of this stuff cost around $5 and made me feel way more talented than if I'd just thrown a box of kraft on the stove. Might want to ramp up the cheese, if you try it, but I was pleasantly surprised by the end result.</p>

<p>A Pitch: The 2011 Ebertfest Rice Cooker Cook-Off. One pot. No rules.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    
        
        <div id="comment-2148030" class="comment">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="comment-header">
                    <div class="asset-meta">
                        <span class="byline">
                            
        
                            <span class="vcard author"><a title="http://carefuleugene.blogspot.com" href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/cgi-bin/mt-comments.cgi?__mode=red;id=2148030">Paul Arrand Rodgers</a></span>
        
                            | <a href="http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/11/the_pot_and_how_to_use_it.html#comment-2148030"><abbr class="published" title="2011-03-28T08:58:51-06:00">March 28, 2011  8:58 AM</abbr></a>
        
                            | <a title="Reply" href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="mtReplyCommentOnClick(2148030, 'Paul Arrand Rodgers')">Reply</a>
        
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="comment-content">
                    <p>Hmmm...this managed not to post the other day. Here's a recipe for macaroni and cheese, for the perusal of people from 2008. If I'm being incredibly impatient with your response to old threads, just ignore this one. My bad.</p>

<p>2 cups elbow macaroni<br />
1 cup heavy cream<br />
1 cup chicken broth<br />
1 cup of shredded cheese<br />
2 tablespoons butter<br />
salt, pepper, cayenne pepper, hot sauce to taste</p>

<p>Common sense dictates that you'd throw in the cheese once the Pot clicks over to Keep Warm, but I threw caution to the wind and tossed the cheese in with everything else. I used a cheap bag of mild cheddar, as I was worried about ruining a more expensive, better cheese, but now that I've done it a few times, I'm pretty sure that the finer cheeses will work and might produce some satisfactory results. Gouda? White cheddar? It will probably all work. For an extra punch, maybe steam some broccoli? Add some bacon?</p>

<p>And, to reiterate something I've tweeted to you a few times, an Ebertfest Rice Cooker Cook-Off would likely fill an auditorium. I know I'd skip a day of work to put my culinary skills to the test. Of course, I imagine Tilda Swinton would be judging, and that she'd love my macaroni and cheese, but this is a distant and unlikely dream.</p>

<p><b> Ebert: I like the idea of the bacon.</b> </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    </div>
        
    


    
    
